Msg.ExtDesc:
The Die and BGA Editor environments use a hierarchical system of placement grids for pin structures. These grids allow you to control the relative placement of pins in an area of the symbol. They also provide the ability to select an automatic pin numbering scheme to apply in this region, so that you are not required to manually enter physical pin numbers.
If you wish to have complete freedom of placement for the pins of this symbol, no action is required on your part. If you wish to make use of the grid structures to simplify symbol editing, please create them before modifying the pin pattern. Any grids you define now will be available for future editing of this component.

There is a non-integer scaling factor for converting co-ordinates between SiP and Encounter I/O Planner. The result is rounding errors with coordinates being off by one or more database units in either tool. See Extended Description for more information.
Msg.ExtDesc:
Converting co-ordinates between SiP and Encounter I/O Planner requires a comparison of the units and accuracy used by each of the two databases. It may also require the consideration of an additional die shrink factor. These things are used to compute a scaling factor from one tool to the other. If the databases do not have the same units and accuracy, the scaling factor in one or both directions might not be an integer. Similarly, if the co-design die is being placed using Die Shrink, there may be a non-integer scaling factor.
A non-integer scaling factor means that converting locations and/or sizes from one database to the other can lead to rounding errors, which cannot be corrected in this tool.
The best situation is one where the two databases use the same units and accuracy and there is no shrink. When that is not the case, it may be possible to fix this problem if the SiP design's accuracy can be changed so that it matches what is in Encounter I/O Planner. It may not be possible to do that if the two tools use different units of measure for the same co-design die.
See the die_editor.log file for complete information on the database units, scaling factors, and other SiP-IOP codesign information for the current co-design die.

Multiple placement grids may be defined for a single symbol definition to allow for different pitch and numbering patterns in different regions. These grids are independent of the system and etch grids defined by the Setup -> Grids... command.
To prevent pins from snapping to a grid, turn the pitch off for that grid by selecting the grid outline (located on the SUBSTRATE GEOMETRY / SYMBOL GRIDS layer) and selecting the "Pin pitch settings" option from the RMB option while in the symbol editing application mode.
